                                <body>                                                
                                                <p><hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE.&#8212;<name type="person">Private Richard S. McLaury</name>, <name type="organization">Co. G, 101st
                                                                New York Volunteers</name>, received, in the engagement
                                                                near <name type="battle" key="48">Chantilly, Virginia</name>, <date type="injury" when="1862-09-01">September 1st, 1862</date>, a
                                                  fracture of the right parietal, and a slight wound
                                                  of the scrotum.  He was conveyed to <name type="place" key="#Washington">Washington</name> and
                                                  admitted to <name type="hospital" key="162">Douglas Hospital</name>.  On <date type="operation" when="1862-10-25">October 25th</date>, a
                                                  piece of bone was removed from the skull; otherwise the wound did well, and the patient was
                                                  sent to <name type="hospital">Jarvis Hospital, Baltimore</name>, where he was
                                                                discharged from the service on <date type="servicedischarge" when="1862-12-27">December 27th, 1862</date>, and pensioned.  In <date type="pension" when="1863-09">September, 1863</date>, <name type="person">Examiners O. S. Bundy</name> and <name type="person">J. G. Orton</name> reported that this pensioner had defective hearing and vision, and that his intellect was impaired and general health seriously undermined. They rated his disability as total. No improvement is noted in the reports since that date.</p>                                                
